3) What is thread Synchronization
When a tread is already acting on an object, preventing any other thread to act on the object, is called "Thread Sychronization"
There can be:
a. Synchronized method: synchronized void display(){ // statements }
b. Synchronized block: synchronized(object){ // statements }


4) What is deadlock?
When a thread has locked an object and is waiting for another object to be release by another thread,
and that thread is aslo waiting for the first object to be relased by the first thread,
they end up waiting for the resources to be released from each other, resulting in "Thread deadlock"

5) Communication between threads
- obj.notify(): This method releases the obj and sends notification to threads waiting to consume this object.
- obj.notfyAll(): Notifies all the waiting threads, waiting for the resolurce to be released.
- obj.wait(): This method waits for the object to be release. It will wait till it gets notification from notify() or notifyAll() methods.

6) Difference between sleep() and wait():
-Both are used to suspend a thread execution for specified time.
When sleep() is called inside synchronized block the obj is still locked, but when wait() is called, it break the synchronized block.
So the object lock is removed and it is now available.

7) Difference between ThreadPool and ThreadGroup
- A threadgroup is a class taht contain one or more threads or other thread groups. Threadpool is concept taht represent group of already created threds.
- A new thread for each task has to be created in case of threadgroup. Threadpool's fixed number of thread will take care of all the tasks.
- Every thread will do their task without coordingating with each other in case of threadgroup. In threadpool all the thread will be in co-ordination with each other.
- Each thread will utilize system resources seperately, thus chance of high load on CPU resources.Threadpool's threads will use only limited respirces, which do not create high CPU utilization.

